        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to use the full polarization capabilities of ALMA in 
Band 7, with an angular resolution of 0.4Í„", similar to that of 
the already available Cycle 0 data. The fixed frequency offered 
in Cycle 2 (centered on LO1 frequency at 343.5 GHz) is perfectly
matching our needs, as it is very close to the frequency that we
observed in our Cycle 0 project  (continuum band centered on 
341.5 GHz), making comparison with the existing maps
straightforward. On the map produced with these data,  
the continuum emission is extended over 2", which is lower
than one third of the 12-m primary beam (18.4") at that 
frequency. The goal of the proposed observations is to measure 
the polarization of the dust continuum emission down to the
intensity level of ~5 mJy/beam - this contour is highlighted in 
the Fig.~1 of the proposal and allows us to probe the emission 
in a region that is already sufficiently distant from the central
source (and the base of the jet) to detect any change in the
polarization level and orientation.

Assuming a polarization fraction of 2%, the expected polarization 
signal is 100 muJy/beam at that position. In order to secure a 
SNR=5 detection, we thus need to obtain an rms of 20 muJy/beam in
the total intensity map. According to the OT, this can be achieved 
in 1.69h on-source integration time, corresponding to a total
observation time of 4.08h. This is larger that the minimum value 
of 3h that s needed to achieve sufficient parallactic angle coverage for calibration.

 </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
