        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity

The science goal is aimed at observing the CH3OH (717-616) line in
the (tentative) disk of HH212. Our Cycle 0 data have revealed
a very compact (fitted size of ~0.25") source. The rms of 
these observations was 3 mJy/beam (0.11 K in a 0.65x0.46" beam) 
with 0.43 km/s (488 kHz) resolution. The line peak is ~150 mJy/beam.

Increasing the resolution to 0.2", we consider the peak flux
will remain the same (150 mJy/beam) or will only slightly 
decrease, since the source has actually an estimated size of 0.25".
In order to keep a SNR similar to that of Cycle 0 data, we 
request an rms of 5 mJy/beam (with 488 kHz resolution). This 
will require 15 min on-source integration time, corresponding to 
1.2h total observing time.

Correlator setup

One spectral window is set on the CH3OH line, with a resolution
of 0.1 km/s (that will be smooth later to the requested 0.43 km/s).
The other windows have been set on various other lines, with the
aim of mimicking our Cycle 0 setup. CO 3-2 and SiO 8-7, in 
particular, will be very easily detected, as these lines are much
stronger than the methanol.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
